val and Early Modern Accounts of Pilgrimage to Jerusalem -- t"The Barbarousnesse of Turkes and Time": Discourses of Travel and History in Seventeenth-century Eastern Travelogues -- tThe "Orient" in Europe? Crimea in Western Travelogues from the Late Eighteenth and Early Nineteenth Centuries -- t"The West of the Orient": The Depiction of the Ottoman Capital in Persian Hajj Travelogues -- tIV Gendered Spaces -- tThe Ottoman Imperial Harem in European Accounts (From the Fifteenth to the Early Nineteenth Century) -- tEffeminate Rulers, Brave Soldiers? "Foreign" Masculinities in Selected Travelogues of Habsburg Diplomats in the Ottoman Empire -- tKeeping One's Composure: Levantine Femininities in Hammer-Purgstall's Travel Accounts and Memoirs -- tV Distant Readings and Digital History -- tThe Reshuffling of Middle Eastern Identities in the Age of Nationalism: Insights from Nineteenth-Century Travelogues -- tGerman-Language Travelogues on the "Orient" and the Importance of the Time and Place of Printing, 1500-1876 -- tIndex -- tList of Authors0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThis volume brings together twenty-two authors from various countries who analyze travelogues on the Ottoman Empire between the fifteenth and nineteenth centuries. The travelogues reflect the colorful diversity of the genre, presenting the experiences of individuals and groups from China to Great Britain. The spotlight falls on interdependencies of travel writing and historiography, geographic spaces, and specific practices such as pilgrimages, the hajj, and the harem. Other points of emphasis include the importance of nationalism, the place and time of printing, representations of fashion, and concepts of masculinity and femininity. By displaying close, comparative, and distant readings, the volume offers new insights into perceptions of "otherness", the circulation of knowledge, intermedial relations, gender roles, and digital analysis.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Egypt (see also Ancient / Egypt).2bisacsh  aOrient.  aearly modern travel.  aperceptions of otherness.  atravel literature.1 aApostolou, Irini, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArgıt, Betül İpşirli, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBauer, Volker, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDemchuk, Stefaniia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDorninger, Maria E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGruber, Doris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGruber, Doris, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHaider-Wilson, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarbsmeier, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuemer, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIngram, Anders, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJost, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKhrapunov, Nikita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnost, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKämpfer, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKılınçoğlu, Deniz T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLandry, Donna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vo